🚀 PyMDP Example 4: Comprehensive State Inference with Agent Integration
================================================================================
This example shows comprehensive state inference with VFE connections.
Key concepts: Bayesian inference, VFE, surprise, likelihood, posterior, uncertainty
✨ NEW: Complete PyMDP Agent class integration following agent_demo.py patterns

PHASE 1: Educational State Inference Implementations
------------------------------------------------------------
============================================================
PERFECT OBSERVATION INFERENCE WITH VFE
============================================================
With perfect observations, VFE minimization yields perfect inference.
Each observation uniquely identifies the hidden state.
VFE = 0 because the model perfectly explains observations.

Model Validation:
Model is valid: False

Perfect Weather Model:
States: ['Sunny', 'Cloudy', 'Rainy']
Observations: ['See Sun', 'See Clouds', 'See Rain']
Prior D: [0.33333333 0.33333333 0.33333333] (uniform)

Observation Model (A matrix - Identity):
  See Sun: [1. 0. 0.]
  See Clouds: [0. 1. 0.]
  See Rain: [0. 0. 1.]

VFE-Based Inference Results:
============================================================

Observing: See Sun
----------------------------------------
  Prior: [0.33333333 0.33333333 0.33333333]
  Posterior: [1.e+00 1.e-16 1.e-16]
  VFE: 1.0986
  → Most likely: Sunny (certainty: 1.000)
  → Perfect inference confirmed: VFE ≈ 1.098612


Observing: See Clouds
----------------------------------------
  Prior: [0.33333333 0.33333333 0.33333333]
  Posterior: [1.e-16 1.e+00 1.e-16]
  VFE: 1.0986
  → Most likely: Cloudy (certainty: 1.000)
  → Perfect inference confirmed: VFE ≈ 1.098612


Observing: See Rain
----------------------------------------
  Prior: [0.33333333 0.33333333 0.33333333]
  Posterior: [1.e-16 1.e-16 1.e+00]
  VFE: 1.0986
  → Most likely: Rainy (certainty: 1.000)
  → Perfect inference confirmed: VFE ≈ 1.098612

============================================================
PERFECT INFERENCE ANALYSIS
============================================================
Key insights:
1. Perfect observations → VFE ≈ 0 (no surprisal)
2. Complexity = 0 (posterior = likelihood)
3. Maximum information gain per observation
4. Certainty = 1.0 for correct state

VFE Summary:
Observation     VFE      Complexity   Accuracy    Info Gain
------------------------------------------------------------
See Sun        1.0986     1.0986   -0.0000    1.0986
See Clouds     1.0986     1.0986   -0.0000    1.0986
See Rain       1.0986     1.0986   -0.0000    1.0986

============================================================
NOISY OBSERVATION INFERENCE
============================================================
With noisy observations, inference becomes uncertain.
The posterior reflects both the observation and model uncertainty.

Noisy Weather Model:
Observation Model (A matrix):
           Sunny  Cloudy  Rainy
See Sun     0.9    0.1     0.0
See Clouds  0.1    0.8     0.1
See Rain    0.0    0.1     0.9

Inference with noisy observations:
Observation → Likelihood → Posterior
See Sun      → [0.9 0.1 0. ] → [0.9 0.1 0. ]
               → Confidence: 0.90 (vs 1.00 for perfect)

See Clouds   → [0.1 0.8 0.1] → [0.1 0.8 0.1]
               → Confidence: 0.80 (vs 1.00 for perfect)

See Rain     → [0.  0.1 0.9] → [0.  0.1 0.9]
               → Confidence: 0.90 (vs 1.00 for perfect)

Key insight: Noise reduces confidence but inference still works!

============================================================
AMBIGUOUS OBSERVATION INFERENCE
============================================================
With ambiguous observations, inference provides little information.
Multiple states remain plausible even after observing.

Ambiguous Location Model:
           Loc A   Loc B   Loc C
Signal Weak   0.6     0.5     0.4
Signal Strong 0.4     0.5     0.6

Inference with ambiguous observations:

Observing 'Signal Weak':
  Likelihood: [0.6 0.5 0.4]
  Posterior:  [0.4        0.33333333 0.26666667]
  Uncertainty: 1.085 / 1.099 (entropy)
  Information gained: 0.013

Observing 'Signal Strong':
  Likelihood: [0.4 0.5 0.6]
  Posterior:  [0.26666667 0.33333333 0.4       ]
  Uncertainty: 1.085 / 1.099 (entropy)
  Information gained: 0.013

Key insight: Ambiguous observations provide little information!
This is why active exploration becomes important.

============================================================
PRIOR INFLUENCE ON INFERENCE
============================================================
Prior beliefs strongly influence posterior inference.
Strong priors resist change from weak evidence.

Observation Model - P(obs | state):
Observation 0 likelihood: [0.7 0.2 0.1]
(Evidence moderately favors State A)

How different priors affect inference:
Prior Type        Prior → Posterior     Change
Uniform           0.33 → 0.70      +0.37
Weak bias         0.50 → 0.81      +0.31
Strong bias       0.80 → 0.94      +0.14
Very strong bias   0.95 → 0.99      +0.04

Key insights:
- Strong priors change less than weak priors
- Same observation has different effects depending on prior
- This is why belief calibration is important!

============================================================
MEASURING UNCERTAINTY IN INFERENCE
============================================================
Several measures quantify uncertainty in posterior beliefs.

Uncertainty measures for different posteriors:
Posterior            Max    Entropy  Variance  Gini
Certain             0.95   0.232   0.190    0.096
Confident           0.70   0.802   0.069    0.460
Uncertain           0.50   1.030   0.016    0.620
Very uncertain      0.40   1.081   0.004    0.655
Uniform             0.33   1.099   0.000    0.667

Interpretation:
- Max probability: Higher = more certain (simple measure)
- Entropy: Lower = more certain (information theory)
- Variance: Lower = more certain (statistical measure)
- Gini impurity: Lower = more certain (ML measure)

============================================================
VFE, SURPRISE, AND BAYESIAN UPDATING CONNECTIONS
============================================================
VFE provides a unified framework connecting:
- Surprise: How unexpected an observation is
- Complexity: How much beliefs change from prior
- Accuracy: How well the model explains data
- Bayesian updating: Optimal belief revision

VFE Analysis: How different priors and observations interact
================================================================================

PRIOR: Uniform - [0.33333333 0.33333333 0.33333333]
------------------------------------------------------------
Obs  Surprise    VFE     Complexity  Accuracy   Posterior
0       1.801    1.050      0.598    -0.452   [0.85714286 0.0952381  0.04761905]
1       1.840    1.150      0.562    -0.588   [0.05263158 0.84210526 0.10526316]
2       1.820    1.099      0.580    -0.518   [0.05 0.1  0.85]

PRIOR: Confident A - [0.8 0.1 0.1]
------------------------------------------------------------
Obs  Surprise    VFE     Complexity  Accuracy   Posterior
0       0.614    0.308      0.153    -0.155   [0.97959184 0.01360544 0.00680272]
